  <h2>Stage 1 — Property Information and Soil Evaluation</h2>
  <p>
    Everything starts with understanding the ground. A soil and site evaluation — typically including a
    percolation ("perc") test — measures how readily the soil accepts and processes water, and
    assesses depth, slope, and layout. This is the single most important stage, because its results
    decide what kind of system the site can support and, therefore, most of what the project will
    involve. It's also why a real budget only comes together after this step. Our guide on
    <a href="/new-septic-installation-cost-factors/">installation cost factors</a> explains how much
    flows from this one result.
  </p>

  <h2>Stage 2 — Design and Approvals</h2>
  <p>
    With the soil understood, the system is designed for the site: the tank sized for the home's
    expected use, and either a conventional gravity drain field or an alternative design where the soil
    or space calls for one. The design then goes through the applicable approval process with the
    appropriate authority. Requirements vary by property and county, and often the installer
    coordinates approvals as part of the project — see
    <a href="/tennessee-septic-permits-and-approvals/">Tennessee septic permits and approvals</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Stage 3 — Installation</h2>
  <p>
    This is the construction most people picture: placing the tank, building the drain field, and
    connecting everything. It's heavy work involving excavation, so equipment access and the lot's
    layout matter — considerations that are more pronounced on the sloped, wooded, or hard-to-reach
    properties common across the Upper Cumberland.
  </p>

  <h2>Stage 4 — Restoration</h2>
  <p>
    A septic installation disturbs a good deal of ground, so the final stage is putting the property
    back together — final grading, and restoring the disturbed areas. Thoughtful layout in the earlier
    stages pays off here and for years afterward: a field placed where it can be reached and maintained
    is easier and cheaper to live with over its whole life.
  </p>

  <h2>Why the Order Matters</h2>
  <p>
    The reason installations follow this sequence — and can't be quoted from a chart — is that each
    stage depends on the discoveries of the one before it. You can't design without the soil results,
    can't price without the design, and can't build without approvals. For new construction, this is
    also why the septic system is best planned early rather than squeezed in late, as our guide on
    <a href="/septic-planning-for-new-construction/">septic planning for new construction</a> explains.
  </p>

  <h2>Getting Started</h2>
  <p>
    Because the project begins with an evaluation rather than a quote, the first step is to share your
    property details and plans so a provider can assess the site.
    <a href="/request-service/">Request septic service</a> to begin, and see the
    <a href="/resources/septic-installation-replacement/">installation and replacement hub</a> for
    related guides.
  </p>
